THE HALL OF THE HONORED DEAD
AN UNEXPECTED REUNION
Kyboah stood before the sealed door of the Hall of the Honored Dead, the rest of the party gathered behind him. The nightshade blossom sat on the threshold like a dark promise. He drew a breath and spoke clearly into the fog-shrouded graveyard:
"Valerius Caelus."
The magical seal hissed and retracted, the ward dissolving like smoke. The ancient stone door stood before them, no longer humming with magical energy. Just a door now. A door they could open.
"Well," Kyboah said, reaching for the handle. "Let's—"
"YOU!"
The shout came from behind them. They spun to find a High Elf woman striding through the graveyard, her finger pointed accusingly at the party. She wore traveling robes that had seen better days, and her blonde hair was pulled back in a severe braid. Her eyes burned with barely contained fury.
"You absolute bastards," she said, closing the distance. "Do you have any idea—ANY idea—what I went through?"
Alfonso tilted his head. "Do we know you?"
"The Pale Lady's tomb!" she snapped. "Winterhold! You left me behind in that frozen hell!"
Recognition dawned slowly. Kyboah's ears flattened. "Oh. Right. The tomb. You got... separated?"
"Separated?" Her voice rose. "I was LOST in that maze for DAYS! Do you know how many draugr I had to fight? Do you?"
She didn't wait for an answer. Her hands moved in sharp, angry gestures as she spoke. "I ran out of arrows on the second day. Had to start using my dagger. My DAGGER. Against ancient Nord warriors in full armor. I tore them apart with my bare hands when the blade broke. I ate snow. I slept in a sarcophagus. A SARCOPHAGUS."
"That sounds... bad," Orion offered carefully.
"Bad?" She laughed, a slightly unhinged sound. "I spent three days thinking I was going to die in the dark, and when I finally found the exit, you were long gone. No note. No search party. Just... gone."
"In our defense," Alfonso said, "we thought you were dead."
"Well I'm NOT." She crossed her arms. "My name is Seraleth, by the way. Since apparently none of you bothered to remember it the first time."
An awkward silence settled over the group.
"So," Seraleth said, gesturing at the Hall of the Honored Dead. "What fresh nightmare are we walking into now? Because I'm here, I'm angry, and I have several days' worth of combat experience to work through. And you owe me."
Kyboah opened his mouth to explain, but she cut him off.
"I don't care what it is. I'm coming with you. Consider it payment for leaving me to rot in that frozen tomb."
The party exchanged glances. It didn't seem like they had much choice.
"Alright," Kyboah said. "Welcome back."
THE NIGHTSHADE CHAMBER
They pushed open the door together. Beyond it lay a small antechamber, and the smell hit them immediately—sweet, cloying, overwhelming. The scent of nightshade so thick it felt like breathing syrup.
The party stumbled into the chamber, their heads swimming. Kyboah's vision blurred. Orion swayed on his feet. Alfonso felt his thoughts slow to a crawl. Even Ja'ha, who seemed less affected than the others, moved with visible effort.
The old Khajiit spotted the source first—a crystal vase on a stone pedestal, filled with nightshade blossoms that seemed to shimmer with unnatural pollen. She pushed through the mental fog and walked up to the pedestal, then smacked the vase off with one clawed hand.
It shattered on the stone floor, the flowers scattering. The oppressive atmosphere lifted immediately, like a window being opened in a stuffy room.
"Better," Ja'ha said simply.
Saijah looked around at the group, then back toward the entrance. "Someone should watch the door," she said. "We don't know if there are other exits to this place. If whatever's down here tries to flee, or if someone tries to escape, we need someone topside."
Kyboah considered this. "You're right. Good thinking."
"I'll keep watch," Saijah said. "Make sure nothing gets past us. If anyone comes out, I'll be ready."
"And if we need to get out fast, you'll be there to cover our retreat," Orion added.
Saijah nodded and left, taking up a position where she could watch both the entrance and the surrounding graveyard.
The remaining five stood in the antechamber, looking at each other.
"Well," Seraleth said, notching an arrow. "Shall we?"
THE PARLOR
The doorway beyond the antechamber led to a gentleman's parlor that looked like it had been frozen in time. Rich carpet, elegant furniture, a harpsichord in the corner. And on the mantelpiece, a silver locket displaying a painted portrait of a family—a man, a woman, and a child, all smiling.
But what drew their attention were the four iron cages along the far wall.
People lay inside them, perfectly still, their chests barely rising and falling. Kust, the blacksmith's apprentice. Hert, the lumberjack. The elderly Salvian couple. All trapped in unnatural sleep.
"Found them," Kyboah said quietly.
Alfonso moved closer to examine the locket while the others spread out to investigate the room. Orion checked the furniture. Seraleth examined the cages with growing horror. Ja'ha sniffed the air, her whiskers twitching.
"These are livestock pens," Seraleth said, disgust clear in her voice. "Look at them. The drainage channels, the locks on the outside. These aren't prison cells. These are cages for animals."
Alfonso picked up the locket, studying the inscription inside. "To Valerius, husband and father. May we never be parted." He looked at the portrait more closely. "This painting is over two hundred years old."
Kyboah approached the cages, studying the sleeping victims. They looked peaceful, serene even, but something was wrong. He could feel the magic radiating from them—illusion magic, far stronger than what they'd found at the crime scenes.
"There's magic on them," Kyboah said. "Strong magic."
"Magical stasis," he confirmed. "This isn't sleep. It's—"
He was cut off when Alfonso suddenly grabbed the bars of one cage and began shaking it violently.
"What are you doing?" Orion asked.
"Trying to wake them up," Alfonso said, rattling the bars.
"I don't think that's going to—"
A door burst open on the far side of the chamber.
A Dark Elf emerged, moving with inhuman speed. Behind it came something that looked like a wolf made of shadow and frost, its eyes glowing with cold light.
The Dark Elf's eyes locked onto Alfonso, and it hissed, revealing elongated fangs.
"Contact!" Kyboah shouted.
THE FIRST BLOOD
The creature that had once been a Dark Elf moved like nothing natural. It came straight for Alfonso, claws extended, and the mage barely managed to raise a ward in time. The impact sent him staggering back.
The death hound split off, going for Orion. The Breton raised his shield just as the creature's jaws closed, frost spreading across the metal.
Kyboah activated his gloves and charged. His glowing fists caught the Dark Elf in the ribs with a satisfying crack, driving it back several steps. It snarled and lashed out with its claws, but Kyboah was already moving, dancing away from the strike.
Seraleth's bow sang. Her arrow took the Dark Elf in the shoulder, spinning it around. It grabbed the shaft and yanked it out without seeming to notice the pain.
Ja'ha had vanished into the shadows—one moment she was there, the next she was gone, moving with a speed and stealth that seemed impossible for someone her age.
Alfonso hurled a bolt of lightning at the Dark Elf. It struck true, electricity arcing across its body. The creature convulsed but kept coming, its movements jerky but relentless.
The death hound lunged at Orion again. This time, the Breton was ready. He brought his sword down in a brutal overhead chop that cleaved through the creature's skull. It dropped, twitched once, and lay still.
"One down!" Orion called.
The Dark Elf turned its attention to him, seeing the warrior as the greater threat. It charged, impossibly fast, but Kyboah intercepted it. The Khajiit's glowing fists became a blur—left, right, uppercut, each strike landing with devastating force.
Seraleth fired arrow after arrow, each one finding its mark. The Dark Elf's body bristled with shafts, but it wouldn't fall.
Then Ja'ha struck from the shadows. She'd climbed onto one of the cages, and now she leaped, her claws extended. She landed on the Dark Elf's back and drove her claws into its neck with savage precision.
The creature let out a gurgling shriek and finally collapsed.
Silence returned to the parlor, broken only by their heavy breathing.
Alfonso approached the fallen Dark Elf carefully, studying its features. The elongated fangs. The pale skin. The unnatural speed and resilience.
"Vampire," he said. "This was a vampire."
The others looked at each other with new understanding. The locked rooms. The supernatural silence. The grave dust.
They'd been hunting vampires all along.
"The people in the cages," Kyboah said, moving to examine them more closely now that they had time. He tilted Kust's head gently to the side.
Two puncture marks on the neck. Clean. Precise.
"They've been fed on," he confirmed.
The reality of what they were dealing with settled over them like a shroud.
"We need to go deeper," Orion said, checking his shield for frost damage. "If there's one vampire, there are more. And whoever's in charge is still down there."
They moved to the next doorway, weapons ready.
THE WORKSHOP
The next chamber smelled of sawdust and blood. Hert's lumber was stacked along one wall, being transformed into ornate shelves with incredible craftsmanship. On the workbench lay Kust's silver fittings—hinges, clasps, reinforcing plates. And beside them, several billets of pure silver that seemed to glow with their own light.
"Silver," Kyboah said, picking up one of the billets. "Lod said to always order extra. 'Never know when you need to put down a monster.'"
"Smart man," Seraleth said.
They split up to investigate. Orion examined the work orders on a desk—each one listing a victim by name and skill. "Hert - Master Carpenter." "Kust - Silver Smith Apprentice." The notes ended with phrases like "Specimen acquired" and "Resource secured."
"He's cataloging them," Orion said with disgust. "Like inventory."
Alfonso ran his hands over the half-finished shelves and felt it—compulsion magic woven into the wood itself. Subtle. Sophisticated. Designed to make anyone who looked at the completed work feel calm and appreciative.
"Illusion magic in the woodwork," he announced. "He's literally building magical manipulation into his collection."
They were so focused on their investigation that they almost missed it. Kyboah's nose twitched, his ears swiveling toward the library door. Ja'ha had already frozen in place, her nostrils flaring.
"Blood," Kyboah said quietly. "A lot of it."
"Coming this way," Ja'ha added, her claws extending.
The door burst open and two vampires rushed in. A High Elf and a Nord, both faster and more controlled than the fledgling they'd fought before.
THE WORKSHOP BATTLE
The High Elf vampire went straight for Seraleth, perhaps recognizing a fellow elf. Seraleth backpedaled, loosing arrows as fast as she could draw them. The vampire dodged the first two, but the third caught it in the chest. It barely slowed.
The Nord vampire engaged Kyboah and Orion, its movements calculated and precise. This wasn't a mindless fledgling—this was a predator that had been hunting for years.
Ja'ha materialized behind the High Elf vampire, her claws raking across its back. The creature spun with inhuman speed and backhanded her. The blow sent her rolling, but she came up in a crouch, her eyes bright with something that might have been excitement.
Alfonso cast a spell, and spectral ice formed in the air, coalescing into the shape of a massive humanoid construct. The ice atronach crashed into the Nord vampire with enough force to stagger it. The construct's fist connected again, driving the vampire back toward the shelves.
"That's more like it," Alfonso muttered.
Orion blew his war horn, the sound echoing through the chamber. Immediately, the party felt stronger, faster, more coordinated. The Nord vampire flinched at the sound, covering its ears.
Kyboah used the opening. His fists became a blur of motion, each strike landing with devastating precision. He caught the Nord vampire in a devastating combo, working in concert with the ice atronach to keep it pinned and battered.
The High Elf vampire had gotten close to Seraleth. Too close. It grabbed for her, trying to disarm her.
Seraleth twisted away, still firing arrows at point-blank range. She pulled a vial from her belt—poison, one she'd been saving—and threw it. The glass shattered against the vampire's face. The poison began eating through its flesh immediately.
Meanwhile, the Nord vampire had focused on Ja'ha. The old Khajiit was fast, her claws finding weak points with practiced precision. But the Nord was faster. It feinted left, and when Ja'ha moved to counter, it pounced.
The vampire's weight drove her to the ground. Its fangs sank deep into her neck.
The party watched in horror as Ja'ha went limp, blood spreading across the workshop floor. The Nord vampire stood, licking its lips with satisfaction.
Then Ja'ha's eyes snapped open.
She moved with speed that shouldn't have been possible. Her claws found the Nord vampire's throat and tore it out in a single savage motion. The vampire stumbled back, gurgling, collapsing.
Ja'ha stood slowly, one hand going to her neck. She looked at the fallen vampire, then at her companions, confusion and something else—something hungry—flickering in her eyes.
Seraleth's poison had done its work. The High Elf vampire was weakening, its movements growing sluggish. Ja'ha was there a second later, her claws finding the vampire's throat. The High Elf vampire collapsed, its movements growing slower, weaker, until it finally stopped moving.
The Nord vampire, seeing its companion fall, tried to retreat. But the ice atronach grabbed it from behind, its massive hands closing around the vampire's arms. Kyboah hit it with everything he had—a spinning strike with devastating force.
The vampire's head separated from its body.
Silence returned. The ice atronach stood victorious, waiting for its next command.
"Everyone alive?" Kyboah asked, the ritual question.
"Alive," came most of the responses.
Ja'ha stood apart from the group, one hand still at her neck where the bite marks bled sluggishly. She looked at the fallen vampires with an expression that was hard to read.
"Ja'ha?" Orion asked carefully. "You alright?"
"This one is fine," she said quietly. "Just..." She paused, her tongue running over her teeth. "Very thirsty. This one is very, very thirsty."
The words hung in the air. No one quite knew what to make of them yet.
"We should keep moving," Kyboah said after a moment. "Find what we came for."
They gathered the silver billets—weapons against what was to come—and steeled themselves.
The library waited beyond the next door.
THE LIBRARY
They entered cautiously. The chamber beyond was magnificent—a grand library in the process of completion. Half-finished shelves lined the walls, already filled with books. The scent of old paper and leather filled the air, almost pleasant after the blood and sawdust of the workshop.
At the center of the room sat a massive oak desk covered in papers and texts. And there, bound in midnight-blue leather, was a journal.
"Spread out," Kyboah said quietly. "Search carefully."
They moved through the library like ghosts, each taking a section. Seraleth examined the book titles. Orion checked the shelves for hidden compartments. Ja'ha prowled the perimeter, her movements unusually fluid and graceful.
Alfonso reached the desk first and opened the journal.
"Listen to this," he said, and began to read aloud:
"It has been 237 years since the plague took them. Livia. Marcus. My entire world, consumed by disease in a fortnight. I begged the Divines. I prayed to every god. Silence. Then HE answered. Molag Bal offered me eternity—time to master death itself, to never again watch talent and beauty wither away. I accepted. I would become the curator mortality never was."
Alfonso continued reading, his voice flat: "The common folk waste their lives in drudgery and then die, their skills lost forever. I offer them purpose. I offer them eternity in service of something greater. They should thank me."
"He lost his family to plague," Kyboah said quietly. "Made a deal with a Daedric Prince. And convinced himself he's doing the world a favor."
A sound interrupted them—a soft flutter, like fabric in wind. It came from above, from the second story of bookshelves that ringed the chamber.
They all looked up but saw nothing.
"Did anyone else hear that?" Seraleth asked, arrow already nocked.
The flutter didn't repeat. They returned to their search, but more cautiously now.
Orion had moved to the bookshelves, running his hands along the spines. He pulled out a volume titled "Debate with the Undead: A Study of Cyrodiilic Vampire Psychology."
He flipped it open and began reading aloud: "Cyrodiilic vampires of the Old Nobility bloodline are psychologically vulnerable to reminders of their mortal past. Confronting them with the humanity they've lost can shatter their carefully constructed justifications and cause profound emotional distress."
"So we can hurt him," Orion said. "Not just physically. We can break through whatever he's telling himself."
The flutter came again. Closer this time. More distinct.
They all froze, weapons ready, scanning the upper levels of the library.
Nothing. Just shadows and books.
"Whatever it is," Kyboah said quietly, "it knows we're here."
They spoke in hushed voices for a moment, discussing what they'd learned, what to do next. The flutter sounded a third time, and this time they all looked up immediately.
The vampire blood-knight dropped from above like a stone.
He wore ancient steel plate armor and a flowing cape that spread wide as he fell, then snapped tight around him as he landed. Not on top of them as they'd expected, but directly behind Orion.
The cape settled around his shoulders with theatrical precision. He was tall, broad-shouldered, his face aristocratic despite the obvious signs of vampirism. His eyes burned with cold intelligence.
He let out a vampiric screech that echoed through the library, and from the shadows, three vampire fledglings emerged to join him.
Orion managed to turn, managed to raise his shield and blow his war horn in a single desperate motion.
The blood-knight's sword came down like a falling star.
The impact sent Orion flying into the nearest bookshelf. He hit hard enough to crack the wood, sliding to the ground with a groan.
"ORION!" Seraleth screamed.
The blood-knight turned to face the rest of them, his cape swirling dramatically. Four vampires now stood between the party and their fallen companion.
This was going to be bad.
THE BATTLE OF THE LIBRARY
Alfonso didn't hesitate. His hands moved in intricate patterns, and the air in front of him crystallized. An ice atronach formed, even larger than the last one, its fists massive clubs of frozen magic.
"Kill it!" Alfonso commanded.
The atronach charged. Its fist came down on the blood-knight with enough force to pulverize granite. The impact raised a cloud of dust and ice crystals.
When the dust cleared, the blood-knight hadn't moved. He stood exactly where he'd been, the atronach's fist pressed against his shoulder. He looked at the construct with something like amusement.
Then he swung his sword in a casual arc that cleaved the ice atronach in two.
Both halves crashed to the floor and shattered.
"Oh, that's not good," Alfonso said.
Kyboah saw the truth immediately—the blood-knight was beyond any of them in single combat. Speed, strength, skill, he had it all. Which meant only one option remained.
He activated everything. Every enchantment in his gloves flared to life simultaneously—ice, lightning, fire. His hands became wreathed in elemental energy, frost and flame spiraling around each other. He became a living storm of magical force.
He leaped, positioning himself for a devastating strike from above.
Meanwhile, Ja'ha had done what she did best—vanished. She moved through the shadows of the bookshelves with impossible stealth, climbing higher, seeking vantage. She felt young again. Fast again. Strong. Hungry.
From her position in the upper shelves, she began firing at the fledglings, keeping them at bay while the others dealt with the knight. Her movements were swifter, more fluid than they should have been.
Seraleth had no interest in stealth. She moved with the acrobatic grace she'd learned in the tombs of Winterhold, flipping and dodging as the fledglings swarmed her. Her bow sang as she fired, dodged, rolled—a constant motion that kept her just ahead of the vampires' claws.
The blood-knight swung his sword in a wide arc. The blade caught the remains of the ice atronach and carved through it like butter, scattering frozen chunks across the floor.
He let out another screech.
Five more vampire fledglings emerged from the shadows. Eight total now.
"You have got to be kidding me," Seraleth said, desperation creeping into her voice.
The new fledglings split their attention. Several climbed toward Kyboah, chasing him through the rafters and high shelves. The Khajiit bounded from beam to beam, and the vampires matched his speed, keeping pace, forcing him to stay mobile instead of landing his charged strike.
The rest swarmed Seraleth and Ja'ha. The High Elf was struggling now. She'd faced draugr, ancient warriors whose movements were predictable. But vampires were fast, coordinated, and they didn't tire.
Alfonso looked around the library, at the chaos unfolding, and laughed. The sound was slightly unhinged.
He made his move toward the blood-knight and the cluster of fledglings surrounding Orion's position. His skin hardened, taking on a metallic sheen as he cast Iron Flesh. Then he activated his racial ability—Ancestor's Flame.
Purple fire erupted around him, hot and angry, the flames of Dunmer ancestors who had fought and died centuries ago. The fire washed over three of the vampires and the blood-knight. The fledglings shrieked and burned. The knight's armor began to glow red-hot.
Orion, battered and bleeding, pulled himself to his feet. His shield arm was useless, but his sword arm was fine. He put the war horn to his lips and blew again, the sound cutting through the chaos. The morale of his allies lifted. He turned to face the blood-knight and raised his sword.
"Come on then," he said through gritted teeth.
The blood-knight, burning from Alfonso's ancestral fire, obliged. He moved with terrifying speed, his blade a silver blur. Orion blocked desperately with his shield, but his broken arm couldn't hold. The knight's blade scraped along the shield's edge, looking for openings.
Kyboah saw his chance. One of the fledglings pursuing him got too close, and he kicked off a beam, sending himself into a controlled spin. He descended like a comet, his charged strike fully powered, every enchantment burning at maximum intensity.
He hit the blood-knight square in the back.
The impact drove the vampire to its knees. The armor cracked. The knight let out a bellow of rage and pain.
But he wasn't done. He looked up at Kyboah with eyes full of murderous fury and swung his sword with everything he had, trying to cleave the Khajiit in half.
Kyboah twisted. The blade missed him by less than a hair's breadth, so close he felt the wind of its passage.
But the blood-knight had already shifted his attention. His free hand extended toward Alfonso, and his eyes glowed with sickly light. The vampiric drain spell hit Alfonso like a physical blow, red energy flowing from the mage to the knight. Alfonso gasped as his life force was torn away.
The knight's wounds began to close. The burns from the ancestral fire faded. He rose to his feet, renewed.
"No!" Alfonso snarled. He repositioned, hands moving in patterns, preparing a healing spell for himself.
Ja'ha and Seraleth were barely holding on. The High Elf had blood running down her face from a claw that had gotten too close. She tried a desperate gambit—her hands moved in a spell pattern she barely remembered.
Golden light erupted from her palms. Sunbeam.
Three vampires caught in the light simply melted, their bodies unable to withstand even artificial sunlight. They dissolved into ash and smoke.
Ja'ha was a whirlwind in the shadows, her claws finding throats and eyes with brutal efficiency. She killed two more fledglings, her movements faster and more savage than should have been possible for someone her age.
Orion swung his sword at the blood-knight. The blade caught the vampire's shoulder, cutting deep. Kyboah hit the knight again, his glowing fists impacting with devastating force.
The blood-knight was burning, bleeding, surrounded by enemies. His armor was cracked, his cape scorched. Alfonso's ancestral flame still clung to him, eating away at his undead flesh.
He let out a deranged roar and swung at Kyboah one final time. This time, the blade connected.
The impact sent Kyboah flying backward, his body crashing into a bookshelf twenty feet away. He slumped to the ground, gasping for breath, blood spreading across his fur.
Ja'ha and Seraleth had mostly defeated the fledglings now, but as Seraleth cast another sunbeam, erasing three more vampires in golden light, she didn't see the last one coming.
It pounced from behind, landing on her back. Its fangs sank deep into her neck.
Seraleth's eyes went wide. She tried to scream but couldn't. Blood poured down her shoulder, soaking her robes.
She dropped to her knees. The vampire released her and stepped back, watching with satisfaction as she collapsed face-first onto the stone floor.
Her body lay still. Blood pooled around her.
Alfonso turned his attention to the vampire that had killed Seraleth. His hands moved in precise patterns. "Incinerate."
Fire erupted from his palms, not the purple flame of his ancestors but the white-hot fury of pure destruction. The fledgling didn't even have time to scream. It simply ceased to exist, consumed by magical flame.
Orion, seeing an opening, charged the last fledgling that was trying to flank him. His sword took its head off in a single clean stroke.
The blood-knight saw his opportunity. With all his minions dead or destroyed, with Orion's guard down, he could end this. His eyes glowed bright, his sword raised for a killing blow.
Kyboah had recovered. Just barely, but enough.
He launched himself from the ground, activating his signature spin dash attack—the move he'd perfected over countless battles. His body became a spinning wheel of claws and elemental fury, moving at ludicrous speed.
He hit the blood-knight with everything he had.
The vampire's ancient armor shattered. His sword fell from nerveless fingers. He tried to scream, but Kyboah's claws had already torn out his throat.
The blood-knight crumbled to ash, his body unable to maintain cohesion. Two hundred years of undeath ended in an instant.
The library fell silent except for their ragged breathing.
They stood among the wreckage—broken shelves, scorched stone, ash piles that had once been vampires. Orion pulled himself upright, battered but intact. Kyboah bled from a dozen wounds. Alfonso's ancestral flame had finally guttered out, leaving him pale and exhausted.
And across the room, Seraleth's body lay in a spreading pool of blood.
They moved toward her slowly, dreading what they would find. Ja'ha reached her first, kneeling beside the High Elf's still form.
"She's gone," Ja'ha said quietly.
Alfonso knelt on Seraleth's other side. He'd seen death countless times, but this one hit differently. She'd survived the Pale Lady's tomb alone. She'd torn through draugr with her bare hands. She'd come to Falkreath angry and alive, and now—
Seraleth's eyes opened.
They were the same amber color they'd always been, but there was something different about them. Something hungry.
She sat up slowly, one hand going to her neck where the bite marks still bled sluggishly. She looked at each of them, confused, disoriented.
"I'm..." she began, then stopped. "I'm very thirsty."
The words hung in the air.
Ja'ha made a small sound—something between acknowledgment and understanding. Because she understood. She'd felt the same thing when that Nord vampire had bitten her during the fight. The death that wasn't quite death. The waking that came after.
"This one is also thirsty," Ja'ha said quietly. "Very, very thirsty."
Kyboah looked between them, at the bite marks on Seraleth's neck that weren't healing properly, at the way Ja'ha's eyes had taken on a similar quality—brighter, sharper, more predatory.
The realization hit him like a physical blow.
"The bites," he said. "You've been infected."
The party stood in the ruins of the library, surrounded by ash and blood and the lingering scent of nightshade, and understood that they'd won the battle but gained something they hadn't asked for.
Two of their companions were no longer entirely mortal.
And somewhere deeper in this place, Lord Valerius Caelus waited, the architect of all this suffering, the master of the hall.
But for now, they had to process what had just happened. They had to understand what it meant that Ja'ha and Seraleth had died and come back different.
The investigation was far from over.
But it had just become deeply, terribly personal.

